{
  "A 50 kg crate sits on a ramp inclined at 30° from horizontal. What is the component of the gravitational force parallel to the ramp? (Use g = 9.8 m/s^2)": "",
  "245 cos(30°) ≈ 212.2 N": "",
  "490 cos(30°) ≈ 424.4 N": "",
  "490 sin(30°) = 245 N": "",
  "490 N": "",
  "The gravitational force is mg = 50(9.8) = 490 N downward. The component parallel to the ramp is mg sin(theta) = 490 sin(30°) = 490(0.5) = 245 N down the slope.": "",
  "A force F = <40, 30> N moves an object along displacement d = <5, 0> m. How much work is done?": "",
  "200 J": "",
  "250 J": "",
  "150 J": "",
  "350 J": "",
  "Work = F . d = 40(5) + 30(0) = 200 J. Only the force component in the direction of motion (40 N horizontally) does work.": "",
  "A projectile is launched at 50 m/s at an angle of 53° above horizontal. What is its initial horizontal velocity?": "",
  "50 sin(53°) ≈ 39.9 m/s": "",
  "25 m/s": "",
  "50 cos(53°) ≈ 30.1 m/s": "",
  "50 m/s": "",
  "v_x = v cos(theta) = 50 cos(53°) ≈ 50(0.6018) ≈ 30.1 m/s. The horizontal component uses cosine of the launch angle.": "",
  "An airplane flies at 300 km/h heading north. A wind blows from the west at 50 km/h. What is the plane's ground speed?": "",
  "250 km/h": "",
  "350 km/h": "",
  "sqrt(90000) = 300 km/h": "",
  "sqrt(92500) ≈ 304.1 km/h": "",
  "Plane velocity: <0, 300>. Wind from west means wind blows east: <50, 0>. Resultant: <50, 300>. Speed = sqrt(2500 + 90000) = sqrt(92500) ≈ 304.1 km/h.": "",
  "A bridge cable supports a load at 40° below horizontal with a tension of 1000 N. What is the vertical component of the tension?": "",
  "1000 sin(40°) ≈ 643 N downward": "",
  "1000 cos(40°) ≈ 766 N downward": "",
  "500 N downward": "",
  "1000 tan(40°) ≈ 839 N downward": "",
  "The vertical component is T_y = 1000 sin(40°) ≈ 643 N. Since the cable hangs below horizontal at 40°, the sine gives the vertical (downward) component.": "",
  "Two forces act on a bolt: F1 = 100 N at 0° and F2 = 150 N at 90°. What is the magnitude of the resultant force?": "",
  "250 N, particula": "",
  "125 N, particula": "",
  "50 N, particular": "",
  "sqrt(32500) ≈ 180.3 N": "",
  "F1 = <100, 0>, F2 = <0, 150>. Resultant = <100, 150>. |R| = sqrt(10000 + 22500) = sqrt(32500) ≈ 180.3 N.": "",
  "A river flows east at 3 m/s. A swimmer can swim at 4 m/s in still water. At what angle upstream should the swimmer aim to cross straight across?": "",
  "arcsin(3/4) ≈ 48.59° upstream": "",
  "arctan(3/4) ≈ 36.87° upstream": "",
  "45° upstream": "",
  "arccos(3/4) ≈ 41.41° upstream": "",
  "To cross straight, the swimmer's upstream component must cancel the river: 4 sin(theta) = 3, so sin(theta) = 3/4, giving theta = arcsin(3/4) ≈ 48.59° upstream from the perpendicular direction.": "",
  "A 1000 N weight hangs from two cables. Cable A makes 60° with horizontal and Cable B makes 45° with horizontal. Find the tension in Cable A.": "",
  "T_A ≈ 732 N": "",
  "T_A = 1000 N": "",
  "T_A = 500 N": "",
  "T_A ≈ 896 N": "",
  "Horizontal: T_A cos(60°) = T_B cos(45°), so T_B = T_A/(sqrt(2)). Vertical: T_A sin(60°) + T_B sin(45°) = 1000. T_A(sqrt(3)/2) + T_A/(sqrt(2))(sqrt(2)/2) = 1000. T_A(sqrt(3)/2 + 1/2) = 1000. T_A(sqrt(3)+1)/2 = 1000. T_A = 2000/(sqrt(3)+1) = 2000(sqrt(3)-1)/2 = 1000(sqrt(3)-1) ≈ 732 N.": "",
  "A satellite orbits Earth and its velocity vector is <4000, 3000> m/s. What is the satellite's speed?": "",
  "3500 m/s": "",
  "7000 m/s": "",
  "5000 m/s": "",
  "1000 m/s": "",
  "Speed = |v| = sqrt(4000^2 + 3000^2) = sqrt(16000000 + 9000000) = sqrt(25000000) = 5000 m/s.": "",
  "A crane lifts a 2000 kg steel beam. If the crane cable makes a 15° angle with the vertical, what is the tension in the cable? (Assume equilibrium, g = 9.8 m/s^2)": "",
  "19600 N": "",
  "19600/cos(15°) ≈ 20291 N": "",
  "19600 cos(15°) ≈ 18929 N": "",
  "19600 sin(15°) ≈ 5073 N": "",
  "Weight = mg = 2000(9.8) = 19600 N. The vertical component of tension must equal the weight: T cos(15°) = 19600, so T = 19600/cos(15°) ≈ 20291 N.": "",
  "What is the normal force in physics?": "",
  "The force of gravity acting on an object": "",
  "The force parallel to a surface": "",
  "The total force on an object": "",
  "The perpendicular contact force exerted by a surface on an object resting on it": "",
  "The normal force is the perpendicular force exerted by a surface on an object in contact with it. On a flat surface, it opposes gravity; on an inclined plane, it is perpendicular to the surface.": "",
  "What is an equilibrant force?": "",
  "The largest force acting on a system": "",
  "A force equal in magnitude but opposite in direction to the resultant, which brings the system to equilibrium": "",
  "A force perpendicular to all other forces": "",
  "Any force that accelerates an object": "",
  "The equilibrant force is the negative of the resultant force. When added to the system, it makes the net force zero, putting the system in static equilibrium.": "",
  "What is static equilibrium?": "",
  "An object moving at constant velocity": "",
  "An object accelerating uniformly": "",
  "A state where the net force and net torque on an object are both zero, and the object is at rest": "",
  "A state where friction equals gravity": "",
  "Static equilibrium occurs when an object is at rest with zero net force (sum of all forces = 0) and zero net torque. This requires careful vector analysis of all forces acting on the object.": "",
  "What is a component of a force?": "",
  "The total magnitude of the force": "",
  "The projection of the force vector along a specified direction (such as horizontal or vertical)": "",
  "A force that acts independently": "",
  "The angle at which the force is applied": "",
  "A component of a force is the effective value of that force along a particular direction. For a force F at angle theta: horizontal component = F cos(theta), vertical component = F sin(theta).": "",
  "What is a bearing in navigation?": "",
  "The direction of travel measured as a clockwise angle from north": "",
  "The speed at which a vehicle is traveling": "",
  "The distance between two points": "",
  "The altitude above sea level": "",
  "A bearing is a direction measured clockwise from true north, expressed as a three-digit angle (e.g., 045° for northeast, 180° for south, 270° for west). Converting to standard angle: standard = 90° - bearing.": "",
  "What is the difference between velocity and speed?": "",
  "They are the same thing": "",
  "Velocity is a vector (has magnitude and direction); speed is a scalar (magnitude only)": "",
  "Speed is always greater than velocity": "",
  "Velocity measures distance while speed measures displacement": "",
  "Velocity is a vector quantity with both magnitude and direction (e.g., 30 m/s north). Speed is the scalar magnitude of velocity (e.g., 30 m/s). Two objects can have the same speed but different velocities.": "",
  "What is a free body diagram?": "",
  "A sketch of the object's shape and dimensions": "",
  "A graph of position versus time": "",
  "A diagram showing the trajectory of an object": "",
  "A diagram showing all forces acting on an isolated object, represented as vectors": "",
  "A free body diagram isolates an object and shows all external forces acting on it as vectors originating from the object. It is an essential tool for analyzing force problems and applying Newton's laws.": "",
  "What is the relationship between Newton's Second Law and vectors?": "",
  "The net force vector equals mass times the acceleration vector: F_net = ma": "",
  "Force and acceleration are always perpendicular": "",
  "F = ma is a scalar equation": "",
  "Newton's Second Law does not involve vectors": "",
  "Newton's Second Law F_net = ma is a vector equation. The net force vector and the acceleration vector point in the same direction. Each component equation (F_x = ma_x, F_y = ma_y) can be solved independently.": "",
  "What is relative velocity?": "",
  "The velocity of one object as observed from another (moving) reference frame, found by vector subtraction": "",
  "The average of two velocities": "",
  "The acceleration of an object": "",
  "The speed of an object relative to the ground only": "",
  "Relative velocity is the velocity of object A as measured by observer B: v_AB = v_A - v_B (vector subtraction). For example, a boat's velocity relative to the shore includes both its own velocity and the river current.": "",
  "What is the inclined plane force decomposition?": "",
  "Finding the friction force on a flat surface": "",
  "Calculating the height of the incline": "",
  "Resolving gravitational force into components parallel and perpendicular to the inclined surface": "",
  "Breaking the normal force into horizontal and vertical parts": "",
  "On an inclined plane, gravity (mg) is decomposed into two components: mg sin(theta) parallel to the surface (causing sliding) and mg cos(theta) perpendicular to the surface (balanced by the normal force).": "",
  "A ship sails at 20 knots on bearing 060°. A current flows at 5 knots on bearing 150°. What is the ship's resultant speed over the ground?": "",
  "sqrt(425) ≈ 20.6 knots": "",
  "sqrt(425 + 100sqrt(3)) ≈ 21.5 knots": "",
  "25 knots": "",
  "15 knots": "",
  "Convert bearings: 060° bearing → 30° standard, 150° bearing → -60° standard. Ship: 20<cos30°, sin30°> = <10sqrt(3), 10>. Current: 5<cos(-60°), sin(-60°)> = <2.5, -2.5sqrt(3)>. Sum ≈ <10sqrt(3)+2.5, 10-2.5sqrt(3)> ≈ <19.82, 5.67>. |R| = sqrt(392.8 + 32.1) ≈ sqrt(425) ≈ 20.6 knots.": "",
  "An engineer designs a zip line. A 70 kg person hangs from the middle, creating a 10° sag below horizontal on each side. What is the tension in the cable?": "",
  "686 N, particularly regarding": "",
  "343 N, particularly regarding": "",
  "686/sin(10°) ≈ 3951 N": "",
  "mg/(2 sin(10°)) = 686/(2*0.1736) ≈ 1976 N": "",
  "Weight = 70(9.8) = 686 N. At the midpoint, two cable segments pull upward. Vertical equilibrium: 2T sin(10°) = 686, so T = 686/(2 sin(10°)) = 686/0.3472 ≈ 1976 N. Small angles mean large tension.": "",
  "A car rounds a banked curve tilted at 20° with no friction. For the car to travel at 25 m/s, what radius is needed? (Use tan(theta) = v^2/(rg))": "",
  "r = 100 m": "",
  "r = 625/(9.8 * sin(20°)) ≈ 186.5 m": "",
  "r = 625/9.8 ≈ 63.8 m": "",
  "r = v^2/(g tan(20°)) = 625/(9.8 * 0.364) ≈ 175.2 m": "",
  "From tan(theta) = v^2/(rg): r = v^2/(g tan(theta)) = 25^2/(9.8 * tan(20°)) = 625/(9.8 * 0.3640) = 625/3.567 ≈ 175.2 m.": "",
  "A construction worker pushes a heavy box along a floor with a force of 400 N at 20° below horizontal. The box moves 12 m. How much work is done?": "",
  "400 * 12 * cos(20°) ≈ 4511 J": "",
  "400 * 12 * sin(20°) ≈ 1642 J": "",
  "400 * 12 = 4800 J": "",
  "200 * 12 = 2400 J": "",
  "Work = F * d * cos(theta) = 400 * 12 * cos(20°) ≈ 4800 * 0.9397 ≈ 4511 J. The angle is between the force direction and the displacement direction (horizontal).": "",
  "A helicopter hovers in a crosswind. Its engine provides thrust T at angle theta from vertical. If the helicopter weighs 15000 N and the crosswind exerts 4000 N horizontally, at what angle theta does the helicopter tilt?": "",
  "20°": "",
  "arctan(4000/15000) ≈ 14.9°": "",
  "arctan(15000/4000) ≈ 75.1°": "",
  "arcsin(4000/15000) ≈ 15.5°": "",
  "For equilibrium: T sin(theta) = 4000 (horizontal) and T cos(theta) = 15000 (vertical). Dividing: tan(theta) = 4000/15000 = 4/15. theta = arctan(4/15) ≈ 14.9°.": "",
  "A ball is thrown from a 20 m high cliff at 15 m/s horizontally. What is the velocity vector just before it hits the ground? (Use g = 10 m/s^2)": "",
  "<15, 20> m/s": "",
  "<15, -10> m/s": "",
  "<0, -20> m/s": "",
  "<15, -20> m/s": "",
  "Horizontal velocity is constant: v_x = 15 m/s. Time to fall: 20 = (1/2)(10)t^2, t = 2 s. Vertical velocity at impact: v_y = -gt = -10(2) = -20 m/s. The velocity vector is <15, -20> m/s.": "",
  "An escalator moves at 1.5 m/s at 30° above horizontal. A person walks up the escalator at 1 m/s relative to the escalator surface. What is the person's total vertical speed?": "",
  "2.5 sin(30°) = 1.25 m/s": "",
  "1.5 sin(30°) + 1 sin(30°) = 1.25 m/s": "",
  "1.5 + 1 = 2.5 m/s": "",
  "0.75 m/s": "",
  "Both velocities are along the escalator direction at 30°. Total speed along escalator = 1.5 + 1 = 2.5 m/s. Vertical component = 2.5 sin(30°) = 2.5(0.5) = 1.25 m/s upward.": "",
  "A kite string makes a 65° angle with the ground. If the string is 80 m long, how high is the kite?": "",
